<div class="container">
<h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
<p class="tagline">Free guide to debt relief, bankruptcy, and when each applies.</p>
<div class="faq"><h3>How do I know if I should file bankruptcy?</h3><p>Three tests: (1) is your unsecured debt more than 40% of annual income? (2) would it take more than 5 years to pay off at your current rate? (3) are creditors suing or garnishing? If any two are yes, bankruptcy deserves a serious look.</p></div>
<div class="faq"><h3>Will bankruptcy ruin my credit forever?</h3><p>No. Chapter 7 stays on credit reports 10 years, Chapter 13 stays 7 years. But most filers see credit scores recover to 650+ within 2-3 years because the underlying debt is gone. Your current situation - late payments, collections, judgments - may already be doing more damage.</p></div>
<div class="faq"><h3>Can I keep my house and car?</h3><p>In most cases yes. Exemptions protect home equity (varies by state, $25,000 to unlimited), vehicles up to $3,500-$15,000 in equity, and retirement accounts entirely. Secured debts continue if you keep paying. We have state-specific exemption guides linked below.</p></div>
<div class="faq"><h3>Is bankruptcy public record?</h3><p>Yes, filings are public via PACER. But employers generally do not check, and credit reporting rules limit how long it shows. The practical privacy impact is small compared to the relief.</p></div>
<h2>Have a different question?</h2>
<p>Email info@openbankruptcyproject.org or visit our <a href="https://openbankruptcyproject.org">main site</a> for the full library.</p>
